                                    <p class="header-text-header-eyebrow--bold">Elevated levels </p>
                                    <p class="paragraph-text--regular-16">Children and adults with Galactosemia will have high levels of Gal-1p in their blood. After an infant has been diagnosed with Galactosemia, their doctor will do a blood test to see how much Gal-1p is in their blood. Once a child with Galactosemia has been on a galactose-reduced diet, their doctor will check their blood again periodically to see how the Gal-1p levels have changed.

                                    </p>
                                    <div class="d-flex" style="max-width:794px;">
                                        <div class="bg--secondary-light-blue mr-3" style="width:8px; height:38px;"></div>
                                        <p class="paragraph-text--bold-14 text-color--secondary-blue">Although Gal-1p is monitored, there is no evidence that it directly causes health problems that people with Galactosemia may experience.</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>

                                <div class="row">
                                    <div class="col-xl-12 col-lg-12 col-md-12 col-sm-12 col-xs-12 mx-auto">
